<div id="review_3513859942" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3513859942" />
    <a title="Erica (storybookend)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2835464-erica-storybookend"><img alt="Erica (storybookend)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595779045p2/2835464.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3513859942?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erica (storybookend)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erica (storybookend)" href="/user/show/2835464-erica-storybookend">Erica (storybookend)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2835464-erica-storybookend?shelf=2020-reads">2020-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2835464-erica-storybookend?shelf=gifted">gifted</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2835464-erica-storybookend?shelf=i-own">i-own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3513859942" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5888011521856256352">I was intrigued with the premise of this book. An immortal man is separated from his wife by her reincarnation. The story follows Isla Thorne in today’s time, she a scientist researching about cells that regenerate (possibly prolonging someone’s life), and then it switches back to Isla’s first life where she first met Rhys.<br/><br/>I liked the flow of the story, as it switched back and forth between the two times. But I had a hard time understanding the science discussed in the story 😅 This probably stem</span>
  <span id="freeText5888011521856256352" style="display:none">I was intrigued with the premise of this book. An immortal man is separated from his wife by her reincarnation. The story follows Isla Thorne in today’s time, she a scientist researching about cells that regenerate (possibly prolonging someone’s life), and then it switches back to Isla’s first life where she first met Rhys.<br /><br />I liked the flow of the story, as it switched back and forth between the two times. But I had a hard time understanding the science discussed in the story 😅 This probably stems from my dislike of science while in school, and so I didn’t connect with that aspect of the story. Thus the ending, where they were explaining the science of immortality or reincarnation, confused me.<br /><br />I felt that Isla’s visions of her previous life was done well. Though it worried her that she was going crazy, it still gave her comfort as she dreamed of this stranger named Rhys. And I did like the romance. It was sweet and they obviously were very much in love during Isla’s first life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5888011521856256352" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


