      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Caryn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Caryn" href="/user/show/1642154-caryn">Caryn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/54624050-once-and-future-wife">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1642154-caryn?shelf=giveaways">giveaways</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1642154-caryn?shelf=paranormal">paranormal</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1642154-caryn?shelf=time-travel">time-travel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1642154-caryn?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3478601075" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10646617527542460531">(I received a free copy of this book from the publisher, but all opinions in this review are my own.)<br/><br/>This novel should be titled &quot;No One Ever Tells Me Anything and I Don&apos;t Know Why&quot;. Isla Belle lives in a dystopia of migraines and crippling self-doubt. In hallucinations that test her sanity, she believes she is experiencing life in Tudor Wales with an evasive, albeit handsome, man. Not unlike her mother, who is an inmate in a bizarre medical experiment, Isla lives under the tight control of men </span>
  <span id="freeText10646617527542460531" style="display:none">(I received a free copy of this book from the publisher, but all opinions in this review are my own.)<br /><br />This novel should be titled "No One Ever Tells Me Anything and I Don't Know Why". Isla Belle lives in a dystopia of migraines and crippling self-doubt. In hallucinations that test her sanity, she believes she is experiencing life in Tudor Wales with an evasive, albeit handsome, man. Not unlike her mother, who is an inmate in a bizarre medical experiment, Isla lives under the tight control of men who claim to have her best interests at heart. In both realities, she is thwarted in her attempts to choose her own path. As she begins to learn the truth about her identity, her past, her family and her health, she finds that she has been doomed to a "romance" that she has not chosen and can never escape. This book is a feminist nightmare.</span>
